variables.EndGame: Represents the decision to end the game at the next available moment.
variables.RepeatSequence: Represents the decision to repeat the current sequence rather than end the game or move to a new sequence.
variables.SequenceComplexity: The complexity of the sequence - determined by the number of unique symbols used.
variables.SequenceLength: The length of the sequence - determined by the number of characters in the sequence.
variables.NumRepetitions: The number of times the current sequence has been repeated.
variables.NumSequences: The number of unique sequences that have been provided thus far.
variables.SequenceSet: If true, the sequence has been decided upon this round. False otherwise.
variables.ResponseTimerActive: If true, the robot has activated a timer and is waiting for the user to repeat a sequence.
variables.AttemptedReengageUser: If true, the robot has attempted to reengage the user in the task.
variables.FeedbackGiven: If true, the robot has provided feedback to the user about their performance.
variables.UserResponded: If true, the user has repeated (successfully or not) the sequence back to the robot.
variables.UserTimeout: If true the timeout expired before the user could respond.
variables.CurrentSequence: A string of characters representing the current sequence provided to the user.
variables.UserSequence: A string of characters representing the current sequence responded by the user.
variables.AccuracySeed: The seed used to generate random errors by the user, saved for reproducibility.
variables.ResponseTimeSeed: The seed used to generate random response times by the user, saved for reproducibility.
variables.UserMemory: A number from 0 to 1 representing the user's ability to recall sequences and instructions.
variables.UserAttention: A number from 0 to 1 representing the user's attention span.
variables.UserReactivity: A number from 0 to 1 representing the user's ability to respond quickly to sequences.
variables.UserConfusion: A number from 0 to 1 representing the user's confusion about the current sequence, with 1 indicating complete confusion.
variables.UserEngagement: A number from 0 to 1 representing the user's engagement in the task at the moment.
variables.UserFrustration: A number from 0 to 1 representing the user's frustration with the current task.
variables.BaseUserAccuracy: A number from 0 to 1 representing the base accuracy of the sequence a user has provided.
variables.UserNumErrors: The number of erros the user has made in their latest sequence.
variables.BaseUserResponseTime: The base time it takes for the user to respond to a sequence. If it equals the maximum value 7, then the user did not respond in time.
variables.ObservedUserResponseTime: The observed time it has taken for the user to respond to a sequence. If it equals the maximum value 7, then the user did not respond in time.
